b"There is, unfortunately, a sort of ''buyer beware' with therapy, in that it may well leave you feeling worse initially before it gets better.
My therapist did warn me of that at the start of mine, but me being me, it took about 18 months before i really started opening up and talking about stuff, so for me the last year was really hard.
It does get better though.

I think there's a point where old defences and coping mechanisms are kinda being opened up and dismantled a bit, but the new ways of managing aren't quite concrete enough, so there is a period where you feel all over the place.
My therapist said it's part of the process, and a sign that real change is happening.

It's not unusual at all, and decent therapists should know about it, warn you about it, and be able to keep you safe while the therapy is happening - i.e by not rushing things and being able to handle whatever you tell them, and be able to 'contain' you and your emotions during the process.
Can you contact your therapist in between sessions if you need to?
I know you've only had the first one, but when things got really tricky for me, my therapist said i could call her if i was feeling wobbly.
I did it twice, and it really helped.
I know they don't generally like to encourage that (contact in between sessions) but sometimes it is appropriate.
Could you tell your therapist in the next session how you've been feeling in between?
It might get them to slow down a bit and take it a bit more gently - they shouldn't really push you too hard at the start as they need to see where you're at and build the relationship.
Hang in there KS, it will be ok."

b"Good Morning KS,I hope you were able to get a decent nights sleep.
Have you ever done the 5,4,3,2,1 game?
It was created by a survivor in the Holocaust.
I've found it works pretty well to bring me back to reality.

You're going to use your senses in the following: see 5 things (if alone its good to name them outloud) hear five things, feel five things (like your butt in the chair etc), 5 things you see, then you do 4 things you hear, 4 things you feel, and 4 things you see.... until you do 3, 2, and 1 thing of the above mentioned.If you get stuck you can just do the same thing you saw, heard or felt over....I see the clock, I see the rod, I see the drapery, I see the clock, I see the clock...I don't know what else to say.
I hope you're able to get thru this sooner than later that's for sure cuz it's really hard to be in your spot.
thought i'd make you laugh with this lil smiley.
Hope at least you might have grinned.Well its off to work for me ...............Take care ks.Parakeet"

b'Keep safe I had the flashbacks to for a long time, My first abuser was my dad to, it is so confusing to love the same person who did this to you, I still struggle with it, I forgave my dad almost right away when I was young, he was a heavy alcoholic at the time and didn\'t remember the two times he did.

His telling me don\'t tell "It\'ll kill your mother" led me to a lifetime of hiding it every time I had s abuse, You were a child, you were a victim, we cannot at young ages comprehend what love involving s is, especially if like me you had a disfunctional family where critisizm is rampant and nurturing almost non existant.The flashbacks when they first hit me felt like a freight train of sickness in the pit of my stomach, they were so disjointed and relentless with the emotional connection you feel with everyone that hits.

Try to think of it like a huge jigsaw puzzle with every flashback you add another peice to the full puzzle, the more pieces you add the slower the flashbacks will be, and the clearer you will understand about yourself.They won\'t be this way forever and you will gain full recall.
Don\'t hate yourself for loving him back you didn\'t know any better, children will do anything to love and for the love of their parents, even when their parents are their abusers.
Try to be patient with yourself.
You will get through this and it will get better.
Do keep seeing your therapist, I know they are triggering especially when your still flashbacking, but they do help you relearn healthy emotions and ways to cope and care for yourself.
Huge hugs'

b"I felt the emotional flatness to, without knowing it I had dissaociated and buried emotions for so many years I really wasn't capable of feeling anything but sorrow, and pain, for myself and for the life of me I couldn't understand why.
It was something that as a child and throughout my first 30yrs I somehow had learned to automatically lock away.

When my first PTSD episodes hit, even though previously I had remembered the abuses I had never emotionally connected with them, they were vaugue recollections I would automatically shut off emotionally, give my head a shake and continue on.

When the flashbacks hit, I would get so overwhelmed by huge flashes of emotion, 100 times what one would normally feel, It was like a grieving process only for myself, the flashebacks I couldn't turn off, rather than simple recall of an event like watching a tv show would trigger these massive emotional rememberance waves, sorrow was total despair, anger became rage, and so on.With the flashbacks things suddenly started to make sense, why I had misdirected all negative towards myself, why I hadn't been able to feel true emotions for so long.
I wish I could describe it better, I wasn't in any therapy at the time and had not seen any doctors.
The flashbacks came on fast, first one or two at day or in my dreams, then dramatically increased over the weeks till they were every few minutes of the day.
I was sure at the time I had lost my mind.
One particular event was the root of everything, the beginnings of a lifetime of disfunctional thinking and dissacociated feelings.
When that flashback was complete, it completed the memory puzzle like an epiphany everything suddenly made perfect sense, but the PTSD symptoms lasted several years even after the full recall.
I still have periods of anxiety/ panick and depression.

I did quite a lot of cbt and rebt though online courses, and eventually with the advice of people like the ones on here did seek a therapist eventually where we delved into some scema based therapy as well.
It seems my emotions go from one extream or another even now, I go from extream hypersensitivity in times of anx to flatness with depression.
I hope some of you can relate and my experiences can help to some degree.
At least I learned now where to place my emotions, and to put them where they belong when they do come rather than reflect everything inward as I programed myself to do as a child.
Hope this helps."

b"The last time i came off the medication 10 years ago, i had done a 2 year tapered reduction.

i stopped sleeping, for well over 2 weeks with zero sleep - i went into severe anxiety that turned into extreme paranoia & severely delusional states - was having hallucinations that were more real than the physical world.
i went back on the medication, but only had 1 or 2 hours sleep a night for 6 months - it's taken years to get more of a recovery from that last episode.
i'd rather be on psych drugs the rest of my life than go through all that again.

i think a lot of it is probably withdrawal effects & lack of proper help/support - i think it's criminal that there isn't more proper understanding & support for people & that so many people are just stuck on drugs.

b"Anti-psychotics are major tranquilizers - These are a very powerful & heavy class of drug.
These drugs greatly suppress the mind/emotions/feelings & senses.

Stopping them you take the lid off everything - you get potentially very severe withdrawal/rebound effects & there is also imo an over sensitivity to all the underlying stuff, which can be 10 times worse (or more) than the original experiences for which they were prescribed.

Some people i think are totally chemically dependent to this class of drug after being put on them, & it's impossible for some people to successfully come off, they go into severe physical withdrawal symptoms - regardless of what is tried - especially regarding length of time on these drugs & dosages, & other variables.

i think some people can get off them, but only with first ideally having & setting in place proper resolution to the underlying difficulties, & proper help & support - without that things are hard to impossible.

Where we find that genuine understanding & support i am also at a loss to say as well - i haven't been able to access it in any meaningful way that i feel is appropriate to my own circumstances & difficulties either."
